  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n## 2026-04-25 01:44 UTC \u2014 [P4: Alpha Research] Move the Leading Candidate Refinement and ABC Minority-Thesis Update Onto a Durable Research Surface So It Does Not Live Only in the Worklog\n\n**Task:** Check whether the leading high-bias refinement candidate and the strengthened ABC minority-thesis read are documented anywhere durable outside `WORKLOG.md`, and patch a research surface if needed.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- The repo already had the high-bias refinement candidate documented in `reports/weekly-review-2026-W13.md`, but the richer ABC follow-up and the current combined read were not captured in the main trader-analysis note.\n- Patched `research/trader-analysis-2026-04-24.md` to add a follow-up note that now records:\n  - `ABC` as a **persistent clean minority `SOL > HYPE` thesis**\n  - `max_bias=70` as the current preferred ceiling\n  - the shadow candidate rule `if |bias| >= 65 and |macd_h| < 10: block`\n\n**My thinking:**\nI\u2019m glad this is now on a durable research surface. Worklogs are great for flow, but decisions get lost there. The trader-analysis file is a much better place for future me to rediscover the actual state of play without replaying an entire heartbeat chain.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Treat the trader-analysis note as updated canonical context for this cluster of findings.\n- Keep the worklog for ongoing iteration, but do not let key conclusions stay trapped there.\n\n**Next:** On the next P4 heartbeat, check whether any daily or weekly report surface still needs the same ABC minority-thesis upgrade so cross-file narrative drift stays low.\n\n## 2026-04-25 01:43 UTC \u2014 [P3: Strategy Development] Check Whether the Leading Candidate Rule Is Secretly Just a 20 UTC Fix in Disguise, or Whether It Improves the Cleaner Core Hours Too\n\n**Task:** Break the leading `65+ weak-MACD` candidate rule down by hour to see where its benefit actually comes from.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- Baseline upper-band (`55+`) hour stats:\n  - `11 UTC`: `3` trades, `66.7%` WR, `+0.288` EV\n  - `12 UTC`: `5` trades, `80.0%` WR, `+0.542` EV\n  - `20 UTC`: `1` trade, `0.0%` WR, `-1.000` EV\n- With the candidate rule applied:\n  - `11 UTC`: unchanged at `3` trades, `66.7%` WR, `+0.288` EV\n  - `12 UTC`: improves to `4` trades, `100%` WR, `+0.927` EV\n  - `20 UTC`: disappears entirely because its only qualifying trade is blocked\n- Blocked trades are:\n  - `20 UTC` loss (`bias -65.8`, `macd -7.77`)\n  - `12 UTC` loss (`bias -66.8`, `macd -2.31`)\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is better than I expected. The rule is not just a disguised way of cleaning up the probationary `20 UTC` hour. It also improves the strong `12 UTC` core by filtering a bad extreme-bias case there. That makes the candidate more credible, because its value is not dependent on a single fragile hour.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Keep the candidate rule at the top of the refinement shortlist.\n- Treat it as a cross-hour quality",
